The hot work permit and associated Job Safety Analysis (JSAs) contains the following information:

¿	The effective date and time;

¿	The place of use;

¿	The hours during which the source of ignition may be used, not to exceed 24 hours;

¿	The specific location or piece of equipment where the source of ignition will be used; 

¿	The nature of the use of the source of ignition; and,

¿	Any special precautions or limitations to be observed before, during, or after the use of the source of ignition, including the need for a fire watch and fire hoses or extinguishers. The criteria for needing a fire watch and the responsibilities of the fire watch are identified within the hot work permit.

Safety (including hot work) permits are issued at the job site. The issuer of the permit performs an inspection of the area to ensure the following prior to authorization of the hot work permit:

¿	The source of ignition may be safely used. The site procedure requires that only approved apparatus be used and that personnel performing the hot work (including contractors) be informed of the hazards and properly trained. Also, the flammable gas or vapor content in the air must be less than 0% of the lowest content that is flammable or explosive; 

¿	Combustible materials (including oil accumulations) in areas that will be exposed during hot work are protected or relocated;

¿	Proper fire extinguishing equipment is available to employees performing the hot work.

Fire Watch duties and responsibilities are listed on the back of the field copy of the Hot Work Permit. Personnel in the immediate work area are notified prior to initiation of the hot work to make them aware of the ignition source. This

ndard operating procedures and safe work practices ensure that all applicable personnel will run the MCP in a safe, consistent and prescribed manner proving them to be beneficial to release prevention. MCP developed a written operating procedures program, which satisfies the requirements of OSHA PSM and Section 2760.3 of the CalARP regulation. These standard operating procedures (SOPs) ensure that written procedures/practices are developed, reviewed, implemented, and annually certified as reflective of current plant practice. These documents are primarily accessed online, although hard copies (including emergency procedures) are maintained in the Administration Building in case of a power outage. They may be found within the MCP HSSE Procedures Manual and the Operations Takeover Manuals and are available 24 hours a day. Information contained in these procedures includes:

¿	Steps for each of the following operating phases: initial startup, normal operations, temporary operations, emergency shutdown, emergency operations, normal shutdown, start-up following a turnaround, and safe work practices (lockout/tagout, confined space entry, line and equipment opening, etc.). The latter are covered by a Plant-wide safe work permit system. The appropriate safety issues are also highlighted on the permits.

¿	Tables including safe operating limits (i.e., minimum and maximum pressure temperature, flow, composition) and consequences of deviating outside those operating limits;
	
¿	A troubleshooting guide explaining the steps to correct or avoid the consequences of deviating outside the identified operating limits, including initiation of emergency shutdown;
	 
¿	HSSE sections which provide a brief description of the acutely hazardous chemicals and the associated hazards; engineering and administrative precautions (e.g., ventilation, personal protective equipment (PPE) used to prevent exposures); control measures to be taken if physical contact or airborne exposure occurs,
